ARTICLE I. - IN GENERAL 

Sec. 12-1. - Definitions. 
The following words, terms, and phrases, when used in this chapter, shall have the meanings ascribed to them in this section, except where the context clearly indicates a different meaning: 
Business license tax means a flat rate component of the occupation tax imposed by the county as set forth in this chapter. 
Dominant line means the type of business, within a multiple-line business, from which the greatest amount of income is derived. 
Investigative fee means a fee charged by the county to defray the costs of inspections, criminal and civil background checks, and fingerprinting, or any of them, required for certain businesses. 
Location of office means any structure or vehicle where business, profession, or occupation is conducted, but shall not include a temporary or construction work site which serves a single customer or project or a vehicle used for sales or delivery by a business or practitioner of a profession or occupation which has a location or office. 
Occupation tax means the tax imposed pursuant to this chapter on certain businesses, comprised of and representing the total of the business license tax plus the applicable regulatory fee. 
Person shall be held to include sole proprietors, corporations, partnerships, nonprofit corporations, or any other form of business organization, but specifically excludes charitable nonprofit organizations that utilize 50 percent of their proceeds for charitable purposes. 
Practitioner of profession or occupation is one who by state law requires state licensure regulating such profession or occupation. The term "practitioners of professions or occupations" shall not include a practitioner who is an employee of a business if the business pays an occupation tax. 
Regulatory fee means payments, whether designated as license fees, permit fees, or by another name, that are required by the county as an exercise of its police power and as a part of or an aid to regulation of an occupation, profession, or business. The amount of a regulatory fee shall approximate the reasonable cost of the actual regulatory activity performed by the county. A regulatory fee may not include an administrative fee. Development impact fees as defined by O.C.G.A. § 36-71-2(8) or other costs or conditions of zoning or land development are not regulatory fees. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 6-180) 
Sec. 12-2. - Persons subject to occupation tax. 
Each person engaged in any business, trade, profession, or occupation in the unincorporated areas of the county, whether with a location in the unincorporated areas of said county or, in the case of a business with no location in the state, exerting substantial efforts within the state as defined in O.C.G.A. § 48-13-7, shall be required to register as provided herein, to pay a regulatory fee, and to pay a business license tax for said business, trade, profession, or occupation. In addition, certain businesses may be required to pay an investigative fee, in the amount established by the county, to defray the cost to the county of inspections, fingerprinting, and civil and criminal background investigations associated with certain licenses. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 6-181) 
Sec. 12-3. - Display of registration and proof of tax payment. 
Proof that the required tax has been paid, along with any applicable registration, shall be displayed in a conspicuous place in the place of business if the taxpayer has a permanent business location in the county. If the taxpayer has no permanent business location in the county, such business tax registration shall be shown to the county clerk, the county sheriff, or their respective designees. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 6-181) 
Sec. 12-4. - Line of business to be identified on business registration. 
The business registration of each business operated in the county shall identify the dominant line of business that the business conducts. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 6-185) 
Sec. 12-5. - Registration; effect of failure to pay fees and taxes. 
The registration herein provided for shall be issued by the revenue collection officer, and if any person whose duty it is to obtain a registration shall, after any fee or tax due the county pursuant to this chapter becomes delinquent, transact or offer to transact, in the unincorporated areas of the county, any of the kind of business, trade, profession, or occupation without having first obtained said registration, such offender shall be subject to the penalties provided in sections 1-13 and 12-68. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 6-190) 
Sec. 12-6. - Revenue collection agency; revenue collection agent; subpoena and arrest powers. 
Within and as a part of the county business license and inspection department, there is hereby established a revenue collection agency which shall have the responsibility for the administration of this article, including, but not limited to, preparing and taking applications, collecting fees, inspection and regulation of applicants, reviewing and approving or denying applications, and the issuing of business registrations under this article. The head of the collection agency shall serve as the revenue collection agent. The revenue collection agent and his duly designated officers and inspectors shall have full subpoena and arrest powers in conjunction with any violation pertaining to this article. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 9-250) 
Sec. 12-7. - Inspection of records. 
The county tax assessors, personal property clerk shall inspect the books or records of any business pertaining to employees of the business or person for which the returns are made. The personal property clerk shall have the right to inspect the books or records for the business for which the return was made in the county, and upon demand of the tax assessors office, such books or records shall be submitted for inspection by the personal property clerk, or his designee, within 30 days. Failure to submit such books or records within said 30-day period shall be grounds for revocation of the tax registration currently existing to do business in the county. Adequate records shall be kept in the county, for examination by the tax assessors office at that officer's discretion. If, after examination of the books and records, it is determined that a deficiency occurs as a result of under-reporting, a penalty of $150.00 shall be assessed for the period delinquent. The right of inspection herein shall be limited to those records, which reflect the number of employees of the person business, trade occupation, or profession of the business. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 9-251) 
Sec. 12-8. - Confidentiality. 
Information provided by a person to the county for the purpose of determining the applicability and the amount of the occupation tax or the levy or collection of occupational tax levied by the tax commissioner, pursuant to this article, is confidential and exempt from disclosure. Such information may be provided by the governing authority of another local government for occupation tax purposes or pursuant to court order or for the purpose of collecting occupation tax or prosecution for failure or refusal to pay an occupation tax. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 9-252) 
Sec. 12-9. - Applications of provisions to prior ordinance. 
This article does not repeal or affect the enforcement of any part of any ordinance heretofore passed where taxes levied under such prior ordinance have not been paid in full. Such parts of ordinances heretofore and hereinafter passed as provided for the issuing and enforcing of execution for any tax or assessment required by such ordinances, or that imposed fines or penalties for the non payment of such tax, or for failure to pay regulatory fees provided for in said ordinances, or failure to comply with any other provisions hereof, shall continue and remain in force until such tax, regulatory fee, or assessment shall be fully paid. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 9-253) 
Sec. 12-10. - No limitation of authority of the commissioner. 
Nothing in this article shall be construed to limit the authority of the board of county commissioners to regulate the exercise of business in any unincorporated areas of the county and, where authorized by federal, state, or local law or ordinance, to deny persons seeking a business registration or license, or both; nor shall this article in any way limit the authority of conditions for the registration or licensure of businesses, trades, occupations, or professions. Nothing herein is intended, nor shall it be construed, to limit the police powers of the county with respect to business practices as the same may be established by federal, state, or local law, ordinances, or regulations. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 9-256) 
Secs. 12-11—12-38. - Reserved. 
