ARTICLE III. - OCCUPATION TAXES 

Sec. 12-67. - Purpose and scope of tax. 
The occupation tax levied by the tax commissioner is for revenue purposes only and is not for regulatory purposes, nor is the payment of the tax made a condition precedent to the practice of any such profession, trade, or calling. The occupation tax only applies to those businesses and occupations, that are covered by the provisions of O.C.G.A. §§ 48-13-5 through 48-13-26. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 6-182) 
Sec. 12-68. - Violations and penalties. 
(a)  Any person, manager, agent, or employee shall be in violation of this article and subject to penalties set forth in this section if he: 
(1)  Does business in the unincorporated areas of the county after the registration for said business has been revoked as provided in section 12-101; 
(2)  Fails to make occupational tax returns within the time and manner herein provided; 
(3)  Refuses to amend such returns so as to set forth the truth; 
(4)  Makes false returns; or 
(5)  Refuses to permit an inspection of books when the officers, agents, employees, or representatives of the county request such inspection, during normal business hours, for the purpose of determining the accuracy of the returns herein required. 
(b)  Any person violating this article shall be subject to the penalties set forth in section 1-13. 
(c)  In addition, the county may revoke the business registration of any person violating this article, unless suspension of business is otherwise prohibited by law. 
(d)  In addition, and specifically in those instances in which the county is prohibited by law from suspending the right of the practitioner to conduct business, the county may impose civil penalties as in the case of delinquent occupation tax, consisting of either ten percent of the total amount due or a delinquent fee of $50.00, whichever is less, as determined by the collecting agency. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 6-191) 
Sec. 12-69. - Occupation tax levied on businesses with locations in the county. 
(a)  An occupation tax shall be levied by the tax commissioner upon those businesses and practitioners of professions and occupations with one or more locations or offices in the unincorporated areas of the county and upon businesses with no location or office in the state as permitted by O.C.G.A. § 48-13-7. The occupation tax rate for each business, trade, profession, or occupation shall be at a fixed rate of $100.00. 
(b)  No occupation tax shall be required from those real estate brokers, real estate agents, or real estate companies whose offices are located outside the unincorporated areas of the county. 
(c)  In the case of a business subject to occupation tax for a calendar year, which business has a location in the county but was not conducted for any period of time in the unincorporated areas of the county during the preceding year, the owner, proprietor, manager, or executive officer of the business liable for occupation tax shall estimate the number of employees from the commencing date to the end of the calendar year, and such occupation tax shall be paid according to said estimate. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 6-183; Res. of 11-1-2005(2)) 
Sec. 12-70. - Occupation tax levied on businesses with no location in the state. 
An occupation tax is hereby imposed on each business and practitioner of a profession with no location or office in the state, but whose largest dollar volume of business in the state is done in the county, and, provided that, the business or practitioner: 
(1)  Has one or more employees or agents who exert substantial efforts within the jurisdiction of the unincorporated areas of the county for the purpose of soliciting business or serving customers or clients; or 
(2)  Owns personal or real property which generates income and which is located within the jurisdiction of the unincorporated areas of the county. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 6-184) 
Sec. 12-71. - Occupation tax levied on certain practitioners of professions. 
Practitioners of professions as described in O.C.G.A. § 48-13-9(c)(1) through (18) shall be subject to the flat rate occupational tax levied by the tax commissioner. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 6-186) 
Sec. 12-72. - Exemption for businesses operated for charitable purpose. 
No business subject to occupation tax by the tax commissioner shall be exempt from tax on the ground that such business is operated for a charitable purpose unless 50 percent or more of the entire proceeds from said business are devoted to such charitable purpose. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 6-187) 
Sec. 12-73. - Businesses not subject to this article. 
The following businesses are not subject to occupation tax under this this article but may be assessed an occupation tax or other type of tax pursuant to the provisions of other general laws of the state or by local law: 
(1)  Those businesses regulated by the state public service commission; 
(2)  Those electric service businesses organized under O.C.G.A. tit. 46, ch. 3; 
(3)  Any farm operation for the production from or on the land of agricultural products, but not including agribusiness; 
(4)  Cooperative marketing associations governed by O.C.G.A. § 2-10-105; 
(5)  Insurance companies governed by O.C.G.A. § 33-8-8 et seq.; 
(6)  Motor common carriers governed by O.C.G.A. § 46-7-15; 
(7)  Those businesses governed by O.C.G.A. § 48-5-355 (businesses that purchase carload lots of guano, meats, meal, flour, bran, cottonseed, or cottonseed meal and hulls); 
(8)  Agricultural products and livestock raised in the state governed by O.C.G.A. § 48-5-356; 
(9)  Depository financial institutions governed by O.C.G.A. § 48-6-93; 
(10)  Facilities operated by a charitable trust governed by O.C.G.A. § 48-13-55; and 
(11)  Any state or local authority or nonprofit organization. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 6-188) 
Sec. 12-74. - Occupation tax not applicable where prohibited or exempted by law. 
An occupation tax shall not apply to the gross receipts of any part of a business where such levy is prohibited or exempted by federal or state law. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 6-189) 
Sec. 12-75. - Occupation tax limitations. 
(a)  The county shall not require the payment of more than one occupation tax for each location of a business. 
(b)  If a person with no location or office in the county provides to the county proof of payment of a local business or occupation tax in another state which purports to tax the person's gross receipts in this state, then the person shall be exempt from the occupation tax levied by the tax commissioner. 
(c)  A person who has locations or offices elsewhere in the state who is subject to occupation tax by more than one local government in the state shall be subject to occupation tax by the county unless the person provides documentation to the county of current payment of an occupation tax, measured by the gross receipts of the person, to the other state local governments. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 6-190) 
Sec. 12-76. - No fee for determining if occupation tax was paid to another local government. 
The county shall not require the payment of a fee in any amount by a business or practitioner for the cost of ascertaining whether such a business or practitioner has paid occupation tax to another local government. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 6-188) 
Secs. 12-77—12-95. - Reserved. 
ARTICLE IV. - BUSINESS LICENSES 

Sec. 12-96. - Business license issued; violation for failure to pay and obtain license. 
(a)  Upon payment of the occupation tax and regulatory fee, or any such combination thereof as required in this article, the applicant, person, business, trade, profession, or occupation shall receive a business license, which shall be displayed in a conspicuous place in the place of business, if the taxpayer has a permanent business location in the county. If the taxpayer has no permanent business location in the county, such business license shall be shown to any police office or enforcement officer of said county upon request. 
(b)  It shall be a violation of this article for any person to operate or conduct a business, trade, profession, or occupation in the county, whether with a location in the unincorporated areas of the county or a business with no location in the state exerting substantial efforts within the state as defined by O.C.G.A. § 48-13-7, or to exercise, conduct, or operate any business subject to a regulatory fee, without having first filed a return for payment of the applicable occupation tax and regulatory fee (or such combination as applicable to said person) paid the applicable occupation tax and regulatory fee (or such combination thereof as applicable to said person), and obtained and displayed a business license. Where a person is subject to paying an occupation tax, and regulatory fee under this article, said person shall obtain one business license, which shall reflect payment of all such charges. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 8-230) 
Sec. 12-97. - When tax due and payable; effect of transacting business when tax delinquent. 
(a)  A registration and occupation tax shall be payable on January 1 of each year and shall, if not paid by April 1 of each year, be subject to penalties for delinquencies prescribed in this article. The regulatory fee, and occupation tax, as applicable, shall be delinquent if not obtained immediately upon beginning business, and a penalty of $50.00 shall be imposed. The tax registration herein provided shall be issued by the revenue collection officer, and if any person, firm, or corporation whose duty it is to obtain a registration shall, after said registration, such offender shall, upon conviction by the magistrate court of the county, be subject to penalties as set forth in section 1-13. 
(b)  In addition to the above remedies, the county marshal may proceed to collect in the same manner as provided by law for tax executions. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 8-231) 
Sec. 12-98. - Evidence of state registration required if applicable; state registration to be displayed. 
(a)  Each person who is licensed by the secretary of state pursuant to O.C.G.A. § 43-1-1 et seq. shall provide evidence of proper and current licensure before the county registration may be issued. 
(b)  Each person who is licensed by the state shall post the state license in a conspicuous place in the licensee's place of business and shall keep the license there at all times while the license remains valid. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 8-232) 
Sec. 12-99. - Evidence of qualification required if applicable. 
Any business required to obtain health permits, bonds, certificates of qualification, certificates of competency, or any other regulatory matter shall first, before the issuance of a county business registration, show evidence that such requirements have been met. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 8-233) 
Sec. 12-100. - Due date; court penalty and interest. 
A penalty is imposed on each business and practitioner of an occupation which fails to apply for and obtain appropriate registration and to pay any and all regulatory and administrative fees and occupation taxes required by this chapter. Said penalty shall be in the amount of $50.00 determined to be due and owing under the provisions of this article. Such delinquency shall also bear interest at the rate of 1 1/2 percent for each month or partial month of such delinquency. Penalties provided herein shall be in addition to any other penalties, civil or criminal, which may be applicable. Such penalties should become effective when such regulatory and administrative fees and occupation taxes remain due and unpaid for 15 days from the due date of the tax or fee. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 8-234) 
Sec. 12-101. - Revocation. 
Failure of any person to pay an applicable regulatory fee or occupation tax, or any part thereof, before it becomes delinquent, or upon the failure to permit inspection of books as required, shall result in any business tax certificates or regulatory fee certificates granted by the county under this article permitting such person to do business in the unincorporated areas of the county for the current year being automatically revoked without any further action required of the county. No new occupation tax certificate or regulatory fee certificate shall be granted by the county for the operation of a business for which any part of the occupation tax or fees herein required are unpaid, nor shall such certificates be issued to a person who has failed to submit adequate records for inspection as required. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 8-236) 
Sec. 12-102. - Execution; liens. 
(a)  The revenue collection agent or his designee, upon any tax or installment of any tax become a delinquent and remaining unpaid, shall issue an execution for the amount of said tax against the person liable for said tax, including interest at the rate of 1 1/2 percent per month accruing thereon. The lien shall cover the property in the unincorporated areas of the county of the person liable for said tax, all as provided by ordinances of said county and the laws of the state. The lien for said occupation tax shall become fixed on and date from the time that such tax or installment thereof becomes delinquent. The execution shall be levied by the sheriff of said county upon the property of the defendant located in said jurisdiction, and sufficient property shall be advertised and sold to pay the amount of said execution, with interest and costs added thereto. All other proceedings in relation thereto shall be as provided by ordinances of said county and the laws of the state, and the defendants at execution shall have the rights of defense, by affidavit of illegality of the tax or otherwise as provided by the applicable laws of the state in regard to tax executions. 
(b)  When a nulla bona entry has been entered by the proper authority upon execution issued by the county against any person defaulting on an occupation tax, the person against whom the entry was made shall not be allowed or entitled to have or collect any fees or charges whatsoever for services rendered after the entry of the nulla bona. If at any time after the entry of the nulla bona has been made, the person against whom the execution pays the tax in full, together with all interest penalties and costs accrued on the tax, the person may collect any fees and charges for services and goods due the person as through the person had never defaulted in the payment of the taxes. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 8-237) 
Secs. 12-103—12-132. - Reserved. 
ARTICLE V. - FINANCIAL INSTITUTIONS TAX 

Sec. 12-133. - Definitions. 
The following words, terms, and phrases, when used in this article, shall have the meanings ascribed to them in this section, except where the context clearly indicates a different meaning: 
Depository financial institutions means state and national banks, state building and loan associations, and federal savings and loan associations. 
Gross receipts means gross receipts as defined in O.C.G.A. §§ 48-6-93 and 48-6-95. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 5-160) 
Sec. 12-134. - Levied. 
In accordance with O.C.G.A. § 48-6-93, there is levied an annual business license tax upon all depository financial institutions located within the county. The rate of tax for each depository financial institution shall be 0.25 percent of its gross receipts. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 5-161) 
Sec. 12-135. - Filing of return. 
Pursuant to O.C.G.A. § 48-6-93(c), each depository financial institution subject to the tax levied by the tax commissioner shall file a return of its gross receipts with the office of the board of commissioners by March 1 of the year following the year in which such gross receipts are measured. The return shall be in the manner and in the form prescribed by the commissioner of the department of revenue based on the allocation method set forth in O.C.G.A. § 48-6-93(d). The board of commissioners shall assess and collect the tax levied pursuant to this article based upon the information provided in the return. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 5-162) 
Sec. 12-136. - Minimum business license tax. 
The minimum annual amount of business license tax due from any depository financial institution shall be $1,000.00. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 5-163) 
Sec. 12-137. - Due date of taxes. 
Taxes levied pursuant to this article by the tax commissioner shall be due no later than 30 days after filing of the return unless extended by the tax commissioner. 
(Res. of 1-7-2003(1), § 5-164) 
Secs. 12-138—12-157. - Reserved. 
ARTICLE VI. - FOOD SERVICE ESTABLISHMENTS 

Sec. 12-158. - Annual service fee. 
There shall be established a yearly service fee for all food service establishments under the purview of this regulation. Such fees shall be proposed by the county board of health and approved by the county board of commissioners. Fees shall become due and payable on a date specified by the county board of health. 
(Ord. of 8-7-1990(1), amend.) 
Sec. 12-159. - Hardship exemption. 
For instances where the collection of fees impose a justifiable hardship, affected parties may present documentation to the board of health and request a waiver of said fees. Service will not be denied because of a client's inability to pay. 
(Ord. of 8-7-1990(1), amend.) 
Sec. 12-160. - Enforcement. 
Upon information being made known to the health officer, his designee, or the county attorney, there shall cause a citation to be issued requiring said violator to appear before the judge of the magistrate court on a day and time certain, then and there to stand trial for violation of this regulation. Citations issued hereunder shall be pursuant to O.C.G.A. § 15-10-63 and shall be personally served upon the person accused. Each citation shall state the time and place at which the accused is to appear for trial. 
(Ord. of 8-7-1990(1), § 1-4) 
Sec. 12-161. - Penalty. 
In addition to all other provisions of this article, any violation of this article is hereby deemed to be a continuing nuisance and may be abated by an application for injunction in the appropriate court of competent jurisdiction. 
(Ord. of 8-7-1990(1), § 1-5) 
Secs. 12-162—12-190. - Reserved. 
ARTICLE VII. - TOURIST COURTS 

Sec. 12-191. - Annual service fee. 
There shall be established a yearly service fee for all tourist courts under the purview of this regulation. Such fees shall be proposed by the county board of health and approved by the local governing authority. Fees shall become due and payable on a date specified by the county board of health. 
(Ord. of 8-7-1990(3), amend.) 
Sec. 12-192. - Hardship exemption. 
For instances where the collection of fees impose a justifiable hardship, affected parties may present documentation to the county board of health and request a waiver of said fees. Service will not be denied because of a client's inability to pay. 
(Ord. of 8-7-1990(3), amend.) 
