In addition to all other provisions of this article, any violation of this article is hereby deemed to be a continuing nuisance and may be abated by an application for injunction in the appropriate court of competent jurisdiction. 
(Ord. of 8-7-1990(3), § 1-5) 
Secs. 12-195—12-211. - Reserved. 
ARTICLE VIII. - PAWN SHOPS AND PRECIOUS METALS DEALERS 

Sec. 12-212. - Definitions. 
The following words, terms, and phrases, when used in this article, shall have the meanings ascribed to them in this section, except where the context clearly indicates a different meaning: 
Dealer in precious metals or gems means any person engaged in the business of purchasing precious metal or gems or goods made from precious metals or gems from persons or sources other than manufacturers or manufacturers' representatives or other dealers in precious metals or gems or a person engaged in any other business if in conjunction with such business precious metals or gems or goods made from precious metals or gems are purchased from persons or sources other than manufacturers or manufacturers' representatives or other dealers in precious metals or gems where the said purchase is for resale in its original form or as changed by remounting, melting, reforming, remolding, or recasting or for resale as scrap or in bulk. 
Gems means any precious or semiprecious stones cut and polished. 
Pawn shop means any building or location where a pawnbroker carries out his business. 
Pawnbroker means any person engaged in whole or in part in the business of lending money on the security of pledged goods, or in the business of purchasing tangible personal property on the condition that it may be redeemed or repurchased by the seller for a fixed price within a fixed period of time, or in the business of purchasing tangible personal property from persons or sources other than manufacturers or licensed dealers as a part of or in conjunction with the business activities described in this definition. 
Pledged goods means tangible personal property other than choses in action, securities, or printed evidences of indebtedness, which property is purchased by, deposited with, or otherwise actually delivered into the possession of a pawnbroker in the course of his business. 
Precious metals means gold, silver, or platinum or any alloy containing gold, silver, or platinum. 
(Ord. of 1-4-1994(2)) 
Sec. 12-213. - Records to be maintained and provided to law enforcement. 
Every pawnbroker and every person engaged in business as a dealer in precious metals or gems shall be required to provide any bona fide law enforcement officer employed by a local, county, state, or federal law enforcement agency a copy of all pawn tickets and other permanent records which said pawnbroker and dealer of precious gems are required to maintain pursuant to O.C.G.A. § 44-12-132 and O.C.G.A. § 43-37-3. Said records shall be kept by said pawnbrokers and dealers in precious metals or gems in such a manner that the said records shall be provided to said law enforcement officers within one hour after the pawnbroker or dealer of precious metals or gems receives a verbal or written request from the law enforcement officer for said records, unless said officer agrees to allow more time. Nothing in this article shall prevent the pawnbroker or dealer and the officers from scheduling a certain day or days of the week for said officers to pick up said records on a regular basis. 
(Ord. of 1-4-1994(2)) 
Secs. 12-214—12-234. - Reserved. 
ARTICLE IX. - GUN DEALERS 

Sec. 12-235. - Investigative fee for the obtaining of criminal histories by gun dealers. 
The county sheriff's department shall collect a fee in the amount determined by the board of commissioners for each criminal background history it conducts on behalf of a hand gun seller with regard to a proposed handgun purchase. The prescribed fee shall be submitted to the county sheriff's department together with a statement of intent to obtain a handgun. 
(Ord. of 3-1-1994) 
Secs. 12-236—12-263. - Reserved. 
ARTICLE X. - WASTE HAULERS 

Sec. 12-264. - Definitions. 
The following words, terms, and phrases, when used in this article, shall have the meanings ascribed to them in this section, except where the context clearly indicates a different meaning: 
Building rubbish means waste material resulting from construction, remodeling, repairs, and demolition operations on houses, commercial buildings, and other structures, including driveways and walks, and it comprises waste and rejected matters such as excavated earth, stones, bricks, plaster, wallpaper, sheet rock and laths, lumber, shingles, tile, concrete and waste parts occasioned by the installation or replacement of plumbing, heating systems, electrical work and roofing. 
Commercial waste collection means the collection, hauling and dumping of household waste, yard rubbish or building rubbish and any other items and substances intended to be discarded by the owner or possessor thereof by any person in exchange for monetary payment or other valuable consideration. 
Dumpster means a large receptacle provided by the county for the disposal of household waste. 
Dumpster site means any location provided to the public by the county for the purpose of disposing of household waste in a dumpster. 
Household waste means that solid waste generated and disposed of, in the normal course of residential living, such as animal or vegetable matter used for or intended for food or that attends the preparation, use, and cooking of meat, fish, fowl, fruit, or vegetables. The term "household waste" also includes paper, rags, plastics, cartons, boxes, cans, bottles, glass, crockery, discarded clothing, and similar combustible and noncombustible waste not subject to rapid decomposition and derived from places of residence areas. 
Yard rubbish means tree branches, stumps, twigs, grass and shrub trimmings, bushes, weeds, leaves, and general yard and garden waste materials and includes stone and dirt rakings and any waste materials resulting from landscaping. 
(Ord. of 8-1-1995) 
Sec. 12-265. - Permit required. 
No persons shall engage in the business of commercial waste collection without having first obtained the proper permit from the county. Application for permit under this section shall be filed in writing with the county clerk, on a form to be provided by the county, and shall specify the name and address of the applicant and, if a firm, corporation, partnership, or association, the principal officers thereof and their addresses, and the address of the premises where the main business office of the applicant is located. 
(Ord. of 8-1-1995, §§ 1, 2(a)) 
Sec. 12-266. - Application fee. 
An application fee in the amount established by the board of commissioners shall accompany the application for permit, which shall be first referred by the county clerk to the county marshal who shall make or cause to be made such investigation as they deem necessary. If the application is approved by the county marshal, the permit shall be issued by the clerk. If the permit is denied, the application fee shall be returned to the applicant. 
(Ord. of 8-1-1995, § 2(b)) 
Sec. 12-267. - Insurance requirements. 
(a)  In all cases, the application for permit shall be accompanied by an original declaration page from an insurance company licensed to conduct business the in the state showing that the applicant carries insurance on the vehicles to be used in collecting and hauling waste in the following amounts: 
(1)  Liability: 
a.  Per person ..... $100,000.00 
b.  Per accident ..... 300,000.00 
(2)  Property damage ..... 50,000.00 
(3)  Medical payments ..... 10,000.00 
(b)  Additionally, the applicant shall sign an affidavit stating that the required insurance coverage is applicable to all vehicles being used by said person in the commercial waste collection business and said affidavit shall be filed with the application. 
(Ord. of 8-1-1995, § 2(b)) 
Sec. 12-268. - Expiration of permits. 
All permits under this section shall expire on December 31, following their issuance. 
(Ord. of 8-1-1995, § 3) 
Sec. 12-269. - Operation regulations. 
(a)  All vehicles used by any person in commercial waste collection business shall be regularly inspected by the landfill manager. 
(b)  No person engaged in commercial waste collection activities shall overload or cause to be overloaded beyond the vehicle's rated weight capacity any vehicle used for commercial waste collection. 
(c)  No person engaged in commercial waste collection activities shall dispose of any such collected waste into any dumpster located at any dumpster site in the county; rather, such persons engaged in commercial waste collection shall deposit all collected waste only at the county landfill. 
(d)  All vehicles used by persons in commercial waste collection activity shall bear on each side of vehicle the name of the person or business entity on said vehicle in letters at least one inch in height. 
(e)  At all times any vehicle that is engaged in the activity of commercial waste collection in the county it shall have located thereon at its highest point from the ground so as to be clearly visible to traffic approaching from any direction an operational flashing or revolving amber warning light and said light shall be in operation at all times said vehicle is engaged in the activity of commercial waste collection on public roads. 
(Ord. of 8-1-1995, § 4) 
Sec. 12-270. - Revocation of permits. 
(a)  The board of county commissioners shall have and does hereby retain the right, power, and privilege of revoking any permits made to applicants under the terms of this article and for violations of the terms of this article. When so revoked, the applicant shall not be entitled to receive back any part of the permit application fee. The applicant may make a new application, if re-examined and re-permitted in the discretion of the board of county commissioner but there shall be no such reapplication or reexamination more often than once a year. 
(b)  The permit granted under this article shall have printed thereon these words: "Subject to revocation by the board of county commissioners for violation of the provisions of the county code of ordinances regulating commercial waste collection." 
(Ord. of 8-1-1995, § 5) 
Sec. 12-271. - Reports of violations; hearing. 
(a)  If any permit holder or employee of a permit holder shall be convicted of a violation of this article, such facts shall be reported to the board of commissioners. The board of commissioners shall then give notice to the permit holder at least ten days prior to any hearing that the board shall hold a hearing to determine whether or not the permit of the permit holder should be revoked. 
(b)  Evidence of a conviction of the violation of this article shall be deemed prima facie evidence of the unfitness of the permit holder to hold a permit and shall be sufficient in and of itself to authorize the board of commissioners to revoke the permit of any permit holder. 
(c)  A notice to be given to the permit holder shall specify that the permit holder has a right to be present at the hearing before the board of commissioners, and shall have the right to have counsel of his choosing present to present evidence to the board relative to the issues pending before the board. 
(d)  Nothing contained in this section shall require or mandate that the board of commissioners revoke a permit for violations of the provisions of this article. 
(Ord. of 8-1-1995, § 6) 
Secs. 12-272—12-300. - Reserved. 
ARTICLE XI. - COIN-OPERATED AMUSEMENT MACHINES 

Sec. 12-301. - Regulations. 
Pursuant to O.C.G.A. § 48-17-15(b)(2), a business owner or business operator, as defined by O.C.G.A. § 48-17-1(2.1), may provide more than nine Class B bona fide coin-operated amusement machines, as defined in O.C.G.A. §§ 48-17-1(2) and (2.3), in a business location, as defined in O.C.G.A. § 48-17-15(2); provided, however, that these Class B bona fide coin-operated amusement machines meet the following criteria: i) it rewards the player or players with tickets, tokens, or other non-cash representations of value redeemable for merchandise prizes; (ii) the outcome of the game involves some skill in its operation; (iii) the award of tickets, tokens or other non-cash representation of value is based solely on the players achieving the object of the game or player's score; (iv) only merchandise prizes are awarded; (v) the average wholesale value of the prizes awarded in lieu of tickets or tokens for a single play of the machine does not exceed $5.00; and (vi) the redemption value of each ticket, token or other non-cash representation of value that may be accumulated by a player or players to redeem prizes of greater value does not exceed the cost of a single play of the machine. 
(Ord. of 4-20-2011) 
Sec. 12-302. - Violation. 
It is unlawful for any person to operate any business in violation of the requirements of section 12-301. 
(Ord. of 4-20-2011) 
Secs. 12-303—12-325. - Reserved.
